Note:
CSS Lexer

Tokenizes CSS stylesheets into a stream of tokens for parsing.

Supports:
- Selectors (element, class, id, attribute, pseudo-class, pseudo-element)
- Properties and values
- At-rules (@media, @keyframes, @import, @font-face, @charset)
- Functions (rgb(), rgba(), calc(), var(), url(), etc.)
- Units (px, em, rem, %, vh, vw, vmin, vmax, deg, rad, s, ms, etc.)
- Colors (hex, named, rgb, rgba, hsl, hsla)
- Comments /* */
- Operators and delimiters

Token Types:
- TOKEN_IDENTIFIER - Property names, values, tag names
- TOKEN_CLASS - Class selector (.class)
- TOKEN_ID - ID selector (#id)
- TOKEN_AT_RULE - At-rule (@media, @keyframes, etc.)
- TOKEN_NUMBER - Numeric values
- TOKEN_UNIT - Unit suffix (px, em, %, etc.)
- TOKEN_STRING - Quoted strings
- TOKEN_HASH - Color values (#fff, #ff00ff)
- TOKEN_LBRACE - {
- TOKEN_RBRACE - }
- TOKEN_LPAREN - (
- TOKEN_RPAREN - )
- TOKEN_LBRACKET - [
- TOKEN_RBRACKET - ]
- TOKEN_COLON - :
- TOKEN_SEMICOLON - ;
- TOKEN_COMMA - ,
- TOKEN_GT - >
- TOKEN_PLUS - +
- TOKEN_TILDE - ~
- TOKEN_STAR - *
- TOKEN_EQUALS - =
- TOKEN_COMMENT - /* comment */
- TOKEN_EOF - End of file
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: Token Type Constants
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_CLASS as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_ID as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_AT_RULE as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_UNIT as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_HASH as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_GT as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_PLUS as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_TILDE as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_STAR as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 24
Constant TOKEN_BANG as Integer is 25
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 99

@Reasoning:
CSS lexing is byte-based ASCII (the spec allows non-ASCII in identifiers
via escapes but the practical corpus is ASCII). The lexer cursor is
byte-indexed and source_length is cached so the EOF check is O(1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 x i64) at offsets 0..32: source (StringCore handle),
source_length (cached byte length), position (byte cursor, 0-based), line
(1-based), column (1-based).
@End Implementation

Type called "Lexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Tokens carry a borrowed pointer + length into the source string rather
than a defensively-copied StringCore so lexing stays allocation-light.
Line/column are stamped at token-start for error reporting. metadata is
a general-purpose slot used by hash tokens (#id vs #hex) and number
tokens (units).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
48-byte record (6 x i64) at offsets 0..40: token_type (TOKEN_*),
text (raw byte pointer into source), length (byte count), line, column,
metadata (token-type-specific).
@End Implementation

Type called "Token":
    token_type as Integer
    text as Integer
    length as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    metadata as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Lexer factory. Validates the source pointer and caches source_length so
the per-character bounds check is constant time. Initialises line/column
to 1 (1-based) and position to 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks source; on null returns 0. Computes source_length via
StringCore.string_length. Allocates 40-byte block; on OOM returns 0.
Writes source, source_length, position=0, line=1, column=1 at offsets
0/8/16/24/32.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new CSS lexer

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer_size be 40
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor-read accessor; returns 0 (EOF sentinel) at or past source_length so
scanners can distinguish EOF from a NUL byte (CSS source rarely contains
NULs anyway).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position and source_length. If position >= source_length returns 0.
Otherwise reads the byte at source+position via memory_get_byte and
returns it.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-byte lookahead for distinguishing comment delimiters ("/*", "*/"),
attribute-selector operators ("~=", "^=", "$=", "*=", "|="), and pseudo-
classes (":pseudo" vs "::pseudo").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position and source_length. Computes peek_pos = position + offset.
If peek_pos >= source_length returns 0. Otherwise reads byte at
source+peek_pos. Negative offsets are not validated; callers pass
non-negative values.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead by offset characters

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, peek_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor-advancing read with line/column maintenance. LF (0x0A) increments
line and resets column to 1; any other byte increments column. CR is
treated like any other byte; CRLF sequences correctly bump the line on
the LF and the column tracking remains consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position/source_length; if past EOF returns 0. Otherwise reads the
byte, increments position. On LF (10) bumps line and resets column to 1;
otherwise bumps column. Returns the original byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If char is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS whitespace per spec: U+0020 space, U+0009 tab, U+000A LF, U+000D CR.
Form-feed (U+000C) is in the spec but absent from real-world stylesheets;
omitted intentionally to keep the predicate fast.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four equality checks against 32, 9, 10, 13. Returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII alphabetic classifier. Used by is_identifier_start /
is_identifier_char to bound CSS identifiers to ASCII letters; non-ASCII
identifiers are not supported by this lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two nested-If range checks: 'A'..'Z' (65..90) and 'a'..'z' (97..122).
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit classifier used by number scanning and identifier tail
classification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range check: '0'..'9' (48..57). Returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex classifier for #rrggbb and #rrggbbaa color literal scanning. Accepts
0..9, A..F, and a..f.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three nested range checks: '0'..'9' (48..57), 'A'..'F' (65..70), 'a'..'f'
(97..102). Returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS identifiers may start with a letter, dash (vendor prefix or custom
property leading "-"), or underscore. The fourth start case per spec is
an escaped char "\xx"; that's handled in scan_identifier directly, not
here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha; on match returns 1. Otherwise checks '-' (45) and '_'
(95) explicitly. Returns 0 for any other byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_identifier_start" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS identifier-tail characters extend is_identifier_start with digits.
'--' is a valid prefix (CSS custom properties), '-' is a valid mid-
character, hence dashes are also accepted in tail position.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha then is_digit; either match returns 1. Otherwise checks
'-' (45) and '_' (95).
@End Implementation

Process called "is_identifier_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralised token allocator. Every scanner produces tokens through this
single path so the layout stays uniform across token kinds.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes; on OOM returns 0. Writes token_type/text/length/line
/column/metadata at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40. text is a borrowed pointer
into source - the token's lifetime must not exceed the source string's.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, text as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, metadata as Integer returns Integer:
    Let token_size be 48
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, text
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, metadata

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inter-token whitespace skipper. CSS exposes whitespace as significant only
inside the descendant combinator (between selectors); the lexer doesn't
emit a whitespace token there - the parser inserts it implicitly between
non-combinator selector tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops peek_char + is_whitespace; on non-whitespace breaks. Uses
advance_char to consume so line/column tracking stays accurate. Returns 1
by convention.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace with char

        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS only has /* ... */ block comments (no //). Comments are emitted as
TOKEN_COMMENT (not skipped) so formatters and IDEs can preserve them
through the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures line/column at the start of the "/*". Consumes the two delimiter
bytes; records start_position. Loops: 0 (EOF) breaks; '*' (42) followed
by '/' (47) breaks. Computes end_position - start_position as the inner
length. Consumes the closing "*/" (two advances). text_ptr points to the
start of the inner comment text in source. Emits TOKEN_COMMENT with that
borrowed slice.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 42:
            Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            If next is equal to 47:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    proc advance_char with lexer
    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMENT, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifiers in CSS include property names, selector tags, function names,
@-rule names (after the '@'), and custom property identifiers
(--my-var). Caller must verify is_identifier_start before calling this.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures source/start_position/line/column. Loops peek_char +
is_identifier_char; on non-id-char breaks. text_ptr = source +
start_position (borrowed slice into source). length = end - start. Emits
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. The token's borrowed text pointer keeps zero-copy
performance.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_id_char be proc is_identifier_char with char

        If is_id_char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS numeric literals are integers or decimals optionally followed by a
unit (px, em, %, deg, rad, etc.). The number portion is scanned first
then the unit suffix (alpha or '%') is scanned and attached as
metadata, preserving zero-copy by keeping a borrowed unit pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures source/start/line/column. Scans digits and '.' (46) into the
number portion. After the number, peeks for alpha or '%' (37); if found,
scans the unit and stores unit_ptr (borrowed) in the token's metadata
slot at offset 40. The token's text/length always cover only the digit
portion - units are accessible separately via metadata.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char

        If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
            If char is not equal to 46:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Note:
    Scan an optional unit suffix (px, em, rem, %, vw, deg, s, ...) and fold it
    into the same token so the token text covers the whole numeric literal
    ("10px", "100%", "1.5rem"). '%' (37) is accepted as a unit byte in addition
    to alphabetic unit characters.
    :End Note
    Let unit_char be proc peek_char with lexer
    Let unit_is_alpha be proc is_alpha with unit_char

    If unit_is_alpha is equal to 1:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set unit_char to proc peek_char with lexer
            Set unit_is_alpha to proc is_alpha with unit_char

            If unit_is_alpha is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While
    Otherwise:
        If unit_char is equal to 37:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End If

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
CSS string literals can use single or double quotes. Backslash escapes are
recognised so the lexer correctly skips an escaped quote in the middle of
a string. The token text covers only the content between (not including)
the quotes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures source/line/column. Consumes the opening quote and remembers its
byte value in quote_char. Records start_position immediately after the
quote. Loops: 0 (EOF) breaks unterminated; matching quote_char breaks
(consumed below); '\\' (92) consumes itself + the next byte. text_ptr =
source + start_position; length = end - start (excluding the closing
quote which is consumed by the scanner ending the loop).
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let quote_char be proc advance_char with lexer

    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to quote_char:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 92:
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    proc advance_char with lexer

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
'#'-prefixed tokens cover both ID selectors (#header) and hex color
literals (#ff00aa). Both are scanned identically here; downstream
consumers distinguish by checking whether the suffix is all hex digits
and 3/4/6/8 bytes long. text covers the suffix including the '#'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures source/start/line/column. Consumes the leading '#'. Loops:
accepts is_hex_digit OR is_identifier_char so both selector IDs and hex
colors are accepted. text_ptr = source + start_position (includes '#');
length = end - start.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_hash" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit with char
        Let is_id_char be proc is_identifier_char with char

        If is_hex is equal to 0:
            If is_id_char is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_HASH, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
At-rule tokens start with '@' followed by an identifier (@media, @import,
@keyframes, ...). The full @-name is captured as a single token so the
parser doesn't have to re-stitch the '@' to the next identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures source/start/line/column. Consumes the leading '@'. Loops
peek_char + is_identifier_char; on non-id-char breaks. text_ptr =
source + start_position (covers '@' + name); length = end - start.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_at_rule" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char with lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char with lexer
        Let is_id_char be proc is_identifier_char with char

        If is_id_char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position

    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AT_RULE, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level dispatcher: skips whitespace, then routes the current byte to
the appropriate scanner. Dispatch order is significant - longer
multi-byte prefixes (e.g. "/*" before bare '/') are checked first.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips whitespace. Peeks current_char. EOF (0) returns TOKEN_EOF. '/'
followed by '*' (peek_ahead) dispatches to scan_comment. '.' is treated as
a class-selector prefix - advance and continue into scan_identifier. '#'
dispatches to scan_hash (if next is hex/id) or scan_identifier (when used
as class-only). '@' dispatches to scan_at_rule. Quotes (34/39) dispatch
to scan_string. Other bytes fall through to per-operator branches handled
elsewhere in the proc body.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    proc skip_whitespace with lexer

    Let char be proc peek_char with lexer

    If char is equal to 0:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 47:
        Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        If next is equal to 42:
            Return proc scan_comment with lexer
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:
        Let class_source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let class_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let class_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let class_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

        proc advance_char with lexer

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let class_char be proc peek_char with lexer
            Let class_is_id be proc is_identifier_char with class_char

            If class_is_id is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            proc advance_char with lexer
        End While

        Let class_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let class_length be class_end minus class_start
        Let class_text_ptr be class_source plus class_start

        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CLASS, class_text_ptr, class_length, class_line, class_column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 35:
        Set next to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit with next
        Let is_id be proc is_identifier_char with next

        If is_hex is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_hash with lexer
        End If

        If is_id is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_hash with lexer
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 64:
        Return proc scan_at_rule with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 34:
        Return proc scan_string with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 39:
        Return proc scan_string with lexer
    End If

    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:
        Set next to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        Let is_digit_next be proc is_digit with next
        If is_digit_next is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_number with lexer
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 40:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 41:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 59:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 62:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GT, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 43:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 126:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TILDE, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 42:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 61:
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUALS, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    If char is equal to 33:
        Let bang_source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let bang_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Let bang_text_ptr be bang_source plus bang_start
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BANG, bang_text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Let is_id_start be proc is_identifier_start with char
    If is_id_start is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier with lexer
    End If

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Return proc next_token with lexer
End Process

Note: End of CSS Lexer
